snippet.textDisplay: I thought the code challenge was rather benign. It seems the comparison operator (either strict or type-converting comparison) should be used (== or === instead of simply using the assignment operator [=]). The reason it will not work is that the variable is assigned a value, rather than checking if it contains that value, and so then the if statement looks at it and asks... is this thing existing in memory with an initialized value and it will always answer yes based on that code sample... thus the coin will always land on heads.
snippet.textOriginal: I thought the code challenge was rather benign. It seems the comparison operator (either strict or type-converting comparison) should be used (== or === instead of simply using the assignment operator [=]). The reason it will not work is that the variable is assigned a value, rather than checking if it contains that value, and so then the if statement looks at it and asks... is this thing existing in memory with an initialized value and it will always answer yes based on that code sample... thus the coin will always land on heads.

I did a quick google search for the definitions of Math.floor and Math.random, and I the only reason I can think of for it only returns heads is due to the fact that Math.random can only output something less than one, and as a result Math.floor takes the doubled random number, which is guaranteed to be less than 2, and floors it to 1, meaning the output will be heads, but there would still be a 50% chance for the doubled number to floor to 0 rather than 1, so it should work. I'm stumped.

snippet.textDisplay: ISO is not an acronym, and its pronunciation is not "i ess o," it's "eye-so" (exactly the way you'd pronounce the prefix "iso-" in any compound Greek neologism featuring that element), as it's meant to be a direct reference to the Greek word "ίσος" (Greek pronunciation notwithstanding).
